<section>
  <h3 class="dummy-h3">How to use</h3>
  <p class="dummy-paragraph">The suggested way to apply a "focus-ring" style to an UI element is using the specific
    <strong>design token</strong>
    provided as CSS custom property.</p>

  <h4 class="dummy-h4">Design tokens</h4>
  <p class="dummy-paragraph">You can use the
    <code>--token-focus-ring-box-shadow</code>
    <a href="./tokens">design token</a>
    directly in your CSS definitions:</p>
  {{! prettier-ignore-start }}
  <CodeBlock
    @language="css"
    @code="
      .your-selector {
        [...your CSS declarations]
        &:focus,
        &:focus-visible {
          box-shadow: var(--token-focus-ring-box-shadow);
        }
      }
    "
  />
  {{! prettier-ignore-end }}
  <p class="dummy-paragraph"><strong>ðŸš¨ IMPORTANT: ðŸš¨</strong></p>
  <ul>
    <li class="dummy-paragraph">the design token as CSS variable can be used
      <strong>only</strong>
      with a
      <code>box-shadow</code>
      property</li>
    <li class="dummy-paragraph">the border radius depends on the UI element to which is applied to, so it's up to you to
      apply the right
      <code>border-radius</code>
      (tip: consider to use the
      <code>inherit</code>
      value).</li>
  </ul>

  <h4 class="dummy-h4">CSS helper classes</h4>
  <p class="dummy-paragraph">We provide also a
    <strong>CSS helper class</strong>
    <code>.hds-focus-ring-box-shadow</code>, that is a wrapper of the design token above, but it's unlikely you can use
    it directly in a template, since this style is connected to the "focused" pseudo-state of an element (more likely it
    would be used in composition with other classes).</p>
  <p class="dummy-paragraph">To use this class you have to import the CSS file
    <code>[products|devdot]/css/helpers/focus-ring.css</code>
    from the
    <code>@hashicorp/design-system-tokens</code>
    package.</p>
